## Typography Principles

### Weight Discipline

**Use exactly 2 weights. No exceptions.**

| Weight | Usage |
|--------|-------|
| 400 (Regular) | Body text, secondary labels |
| 600 (Semibold) | Headings, buttons, emphasis |

NEVER use 300 (light), 500 (medium), or 700 (bold) on the same page as 400 and 600. Mixing weights creates visual noise. Pick two and commit.

### Typography as Design

**Large, confident headings. Serif + sans pairings create sophistication.**

- Headlines should command attention, broken across lines for drama
- Consider mixed typography: a serif paired with a geometric sans
- Headlines can be LARGE — don't be timid with type scale
- Small caps with wide letter-spacing for labels and categories

### Size Hierarchy

**Clear steps, not gradual slopes.**

The eye should immediately understand what's most important. If you squint at the page and can't tell the headline from the subhead, the hierarchy has failed.

- H1: Hero headlines only. One per page. Make it count.
- H2: Section titles. The backbone of the page.
- H3: Card titles, feature names. Supporting structure.
- H4: Rarely used. Labels, small section headers.
- Body: Everything else. ONE size. Consistent.

**Anti-pattern:** Using text-sm, text-base, text-lg, text-xl all on the same section. This creates visual chaos. Body text should be ONE size.

### Spacing & Rhythm

Text needs room to breathe. Generous line-height (1.6-1.7 for body) and ample margins between elements. If text feels cramped, add space. If it still feels cramped, you have too much text.

