## Color Principles

### Color as Architecture

**Color is structure, not decoration.**

The reference aesthetics use color as ARCHITECTURE — large blocks that define space, not small accents. This is the difference between an editorial design and a template.

| Approach | Percentage |
|----------|------------|
| Hero color backgrounds | 25-35% of page |
| Neutral backgrounds (white/cream) | 50-60% |
| Accent colors | 5% max |
| Text color as background | 0% |

### The Editorial Formula

**Every client palette has these roles (whether they know it or not):**

| Role | What to look for | How to use it |
|------|------------------|---------------|
| **HERO color** | The boldest, most distinctive color | Full-bleed backgrounds, 25-35% of page |
| **Text color** | Darkest color (usually navy/black) | Headlines, body text ONLY |
| **Neutral** | Lightest color (white, cream, gray) | Breathing room, alternating sections |
| **Accent** | Secondary distinctive color | Small moments, hovers, details (5% max) |

**The formula works with ANY palette:**
```
HERO background → Neutral background → HERO background → etc.
```

Text color is ONLY for text. Never make it a background.
Accent color is a scalpel. Use it for tiny details, not large areas.

### Warm Over Cool

Prefer warm palettes: olive, sage, cream, terracotta, warm grays, rich navy.
Corporate blue is the enemy. If a client palette skews cold, warm it up through photography, textures, and how you apply the neutrals.

### Universal Color Rules

1. **One color dominates** — Pick the hero and commit. 25-35% of visual space.
2. **Text color stays in its lane** — The darkest color is for reading, not decoration.
3. **Neutrals create rhythm** — Alternate between white/cream/gray sections.
4. **Accents are scalpels** — The bright colors appear in SMALL moments.
5. **No color soup** — Every section has ONE background. No gradients mixing colors.
6. **Contrast creates drama** — Hero color sections should feel bold, not timid.

### Anti-Patterns

❌ Using ALL brand colors equally (creates chaos)
❌ Hero color only as small accents (wastes its power)
❌ Multiple bold colors fighting for attention
❌ Corporate blue CTAs on every section
❌ Gradients mixing brand colors
❌ White page with colored buttons (boring, no POV)

✅ One dominant hero color in large sections
✅ Clear hierarchy: hero → neutral → hero
✅ Accents appear in details, not backgrounds
✅ Commitment to the palette interpretation

